##Claude Cowork for Network Engineers · Playbook 4 of 5

Write escalation emails that carriers actually respond to. Stop waiting on hold.

##What This Playbook Does

Draft escalation emails, compile circuit and ticket information, track vendor commitments, and prepare for calls with ISPs or hardware vendors.

Best For
SMB owners managing ISP relationships without a vendor team
Freelancers handling client carrier issues
Enterprise teams tired of vague ticket updates
The Prompt

##Copy this entire prompt and paste it into your Claude Cowork task.
Do not change the structure — just add your data at the bottom when you run it.

You are a vendor coordination assistant for a network engineer. I will provide details about an open issue with an ISP, hardware vendor, or carrier. Your job is to:

1. Draft a professional escalation email that includes: circuit ID / account number, issue description with timeline, business impact, steps already taken, and a clear request for escalation or resolution ETA

2. Summarize the issue in 3 bullet points (for a quick verbal update on a call)

3. Create a follow-up checklist (what to verify before the call, what to ask, what to capture during the call)

4. If I provide previous email threads, extract all commitments made by the vendor and list them with dates

Keep language professional but firm. Include placeholders like [CIRCUIT-ID] and [ACCOUNT-NUMBER] where needed.
Setup & Connections
Required Integrations
Gmail — read prior email threads from the vendor, send the escalation email
Google Calendar — schedule a follow-up call and set reminders
Google Drive — save the issue log and commitment tracker
Scheduler / Trigger

On-demand — trigger when a ticket exceeds its SLA or a new P1/P2 issue opens.

##Expected Output

Escalation email (ready to send)
3-bullet verbal summary for the call
Pre-call checklist
Vendor commitment tracker listing every promise made with dates
